67 /// Returns true if this lattice value represents at most one possible value. ----
68 /// This is as precise as any lattice value can get while still representing ----
69 /// reachable code. ----
70 static bool hasSingleValue(const ValueLatticeElement &Val) { 0
71 if (Val.isConstantRange() && 0
72 Val.getConstantRange().isSingleElement()) 0
73 // Integer constants are single element ranges ----
74 return true; 0
75 if (Val.isConstant()) 0
76 // Non integer constants ----
77 return true; 0
78 return false; 0
79 } ----
80 ----
81 /// Combine two sets of facts about the same value into a single set of ----
82 /// facts. Note that this method is not suitable for merging facts along ----
83 /// different paths in a CFG; that's what the mergeIn function is for. This ----
84 /// is for merging facts gathered about the same value at the same location ----
85 /// through two independent means. ----
86 /// Notes: ----
87 /// * This method does not promise to return the most precise possible lattice ----
88 /// value implied by A and B. It is allowed to return any lattice element ----
89 /// which is at least as strong as *either* A or B (unless our facts ----
90 /// conflict, see below). ----
91 /// * Due to unreachable code, the intersection of two lattice values could be ----
92 /// contradictory. If this happens, we return some valid lattice value so as ----
93 /// not confuse the rest of LVI. Ideally, we'd always return Undefined, but ----
94 /// we do not make this guarantee. TODO: This would be a useful enhancement. ----
95 static ValueLatticeElement intersect(const ValueLatticeElement &A, 0
96 const ValueLatticeElement &B) { ----
97 // Undefined is the strongest state. It means the value is known to be along ----
98 // an unreachable path. ----
99 if (A.isUnknown()) 0
100 return A; 0
101 if (B.isUnknown()) 0
102 return B; 0
103 ----
104 // If we gave up for one, but got a useable fact from the other, use it. ----
105 if (A.isOverdefined()) 0
106 return B; 0
107 if (B.isOverdefined()) 0
108 return A; 0
109 ----
110 // Can't get any more precise than constants. ----
111 if (hasSingleValue(A)) 0
112 return A; 0
113 if (hasSingleValue(B)) 0
114 return B; 0
115 ----
116 // Could be either constant range or not constant here. ----
117 if (!A.isConstantRange() || !B.isConstantRange()) { 0
118 // TODO: Arbitrary choice, could be improved ----
119 return A; 0
120 } ----
121 ----
122 // Intersect two constant ranges ----
123 ConstantRange Range = ----
124 A.getConstantRange().intersectWith(B.getConstantRange()); 0
125 // Note: An empty range is implicitly converted to unknown or undef depending ----
126 // on MayIncludeUndef internally. ----
127 return ValueLatticeElement::getRange( ----
128 std::move(Range), /*MayIncludeUndef=*/A.isConstantRangeIncludingUndef() || 0
129 B.isConstantRangeIncludingUndef()); 0
130 } 0

155 /// This is the cache kept by LazyValueInfo which ----
156 /// maintains information about queries across the clients' queries. ----
157 class LazyValueInfoCache { ----
158 /// This is all of the cached information for one basic block. It contains ----
159 /// the per-value lattice elements, as well as a separate set for ----
160 /// overdefined values to reduce memory usage. Additionally pointers ----
161 /// dereferenced in the block are cached for nullability queries. ----
162 struct BlockCacheEntry { ----
163 SmallDenseMap, ValueLatticeElement, 4> LatticeElements; ----
164 SmallDenseSet, 4> OverDefined; ----
165 // std::nullopt indicates that the nonnull pointers for this basic block ----
166 // block have not been computed yet. ----
167 std::optional NonNullPointers; ----
168 }; ----
169 ----
170 /// Cached information per basic block. ----
171 DenseMap, std::unique_ptr> ----
172 BlockCache; ----
173 /// Set of value handles used to erase values from the cache on deletion. ----
174 DenseSet> ValueHandles; ----
175 ----
176 const BlockCacheEntry *getBlockEntry(BasicBlock *BB) const { 0
177 auto It = BlockCache.find_as(BB); 0
178 if (It == BlockCache.end()) 0
179 return nullptr; 0
180 return It->second.get(); 0
181 } ----
182 ----
183 BlockCacheEntry *getOrCreateBlockEntry(BasicBlock *BB) { 0
184 auto It = BlockCache.find_as(BB); 0
185 if (It == BlockCache.end()) 0
186 It = BlockCache.insert({ BB, std::make_unique() }) 0
187 .first; ----
188 ----
189 return It->second.get(); 0
190 } ----
191 ----
192 void addValueHandle(Value *Val) { 0
193 auto HandleIt = ValueHandles.find_as(Val); 0
194 if (HandleIt == ValueHandles.end()) 0
195 ValueHandles.insert({ Val, this }); 0
196 } 0
197 ----
198 public: ----
199 void insertResult(Value *Val, BasicBlock *BB, 0
200 const ValueLatticeElement &Result) { ----
201 BlockCacheEntry *Entry = getOrCreateBlockEntry(BB); 0
202 ----
203 // Insert over-defined values into their own cache to reduce memory ----
204 // overhead. ----
205 if (Result.isOverdefined()) 0
206 Entry->OverDefined.insert(Val); 0
207 else ----
208 Entry->LatticeElements.insert({ Val, Result }); 0
209 ----
210 addValueHandle(Val); 0
211 } 0
212 ----
213 std::optional ----
214 getCachedValueInfo(Value *V, BasicBlock *BB) const { 0
215 const BlockCacheEntry *Entry = getBlockEntry(BB); 0
216 if (!Entry) 0
217 return std::nullopt; 0
218 ----
219 if (Entry->OverDefined.count(V)) 0
220 return ValueLatticeElement::getOverdefined(); 0
221 ----
222 auto LatticeIt = Entry->LatticeElements.find_as(V); 0
223 if (LatticeIt == Entry->LatticeElements.end()) 0
224 return std::nullopt; 0
225 ----
226 return LatticeIt->second; 0
227 } ----
228 ----
229 bool isNonNullAtEndOfBlock( 0
230 Value *V, BasicBlock *BB, ----
231 function_ref InitFn) { ----
232 BlockCacheEntry *Entry = getOrCreateBlockEntry(BB); 0
233 if (!Entry->NonNullPointers) { 0
234 Entry->NonNullPointers = InitFn(BB); 0
235 for (Value *V : *Entry->NonNullPointers) 0
236 addValueHandle(V); 0
237 } ----
238 ----
239 return Entry->NonNullPointers->count(V); 0
240 } ----
241 ----
242 /// clear - Empty the cache. ----
243 void clear() { 0
244 BlockCache.clear(); 0
245 ValueHandles.clear(); 0
246 } 0

255 /// Updates the cache to remove any influence an overdefined value in ----
256 /// OldSucc might have (unless also overdefined in NewSucc). This just ----
257 /// flushes elements from the cache and does not add any. ----
258 void threadEdgeImpl(BasicBlock *OldSucc,BasicBlock *NewSucc); ----
259 }; ----

262 void LazyValueInfoCache::eraseValue(Value *V) { 0
263 for (auto &Pair : BlockCache) { 0
264 Pair.second->LatticeElements.erase(V); 0
265 Pair.second->OverDefined.erase(V); 0
266 if (Pair.second->NonNullPointers) 0
267 Pair.second->NonNullPointers->erase(V); 0
268 } ----
269 ----
270 auto HandleIt = ValueHandles.find_as(V); 0
271 if (HandleIt != ValueHandles.end()) 0
272 ValueHandles.erase(HandleIt); 0
273 } 0

275 void LVIValueHandle::deleted() { 0
276 // This erasure deallocates *this, so it MUST happen after we're done ----
277 // using any and all members of *this. ----
278 Parent->eraseValue(*this); 0
279 } 0

282 BlockCache.erase(BB); 0
283 } 0
284 ----
285 void LazyValueInfoCache::threadEdgeImpl(BasicBlock *OldSucc, 0
286 BasicBlock *NewSucc) { ----
287 // When an edge in the graph has been threaded, values that we could not ----
288 // determine a value for before (i.e. were marked overdefined) may be ----
289 // possible to solve now. We do NOT try to proactively update these values. ----
290 // Instead, we clear their entries from the cache, and allow lazy updating to ----
291 // recompute them when needed. ----
292 ----
293 // The updating process is fairly simple: we need to drop cached info ----
294 // for all values that were marked overdefined in OldSucc, and for those same ----
295 // values in any successor of OldSucc (except NewSucc) in which they were ----
296 // also marked overdefined. ----
297 std::vector worklist; 0
298 worklist.push_back(OldSucc); 0
299 ----
300 const BlockCacheEntry *Entry = getBlockEntry(OldSucc); 0
301 if (!Entry || Entry->OverDefined.empty()) 0
302 return; // Nothing to process here. 0
303 SmallVector ValsToClear(Entry->OverDefined.begin(), ----
304 Entry->OverDefined.end()); 0
305 ----
306 // Use a worklist to perform a depth-first search of OldSucc's successors. ----
307 // NOTE: We do not need a visited list since any blocks we have already ----
308 // visited will have had their overdefined markers cleared already, and we ----
309 // thus won't loop to their successors. ----
310 while (!worklist.empty()) { 0
311 BasicBlock *ToUpdate = worklist.back(); 0
312 worklist.pop_back(); 0
313 ----
314 // Skip blocks only accessible through NewSucc. ----
315 if (ToUpdate == NewSucc) continue; 0
316 ----
317 // If a value was marked overdefined in OldSucc, and is here too... ----
318 auto OI = BlockCache.find_as(ToUpdate); 0
319 if (OI == BlockCache.end() || OI->second->OverDefined.empty()) 0
320 continue; 0
321 auto &ValueSet = OI->second->OverDefined; 0
322 ----
323 bool changed = false; 0
324 for (Value *V : ValsToClear) { 0
325 if (!ValueSet.erase(V)) 0
326 continue; 0
327 ----
328 // If we removed anything, then we potentially need to update ----
329 // blocks successors too. ----
330 changed = true; 0
331 } ----
332 ----
333 if (!changed) continue; 0
334 ----
335 llvm::append_range(worklist, successors(ToUpdate)); 0
336 } ----
337 } 0

377 ----
378 /// Push BV onto BlockValueStack unless it's already in there. ----
379 /// Returns true on success. ----
380 bool pushBlockValue(const std::pair &BV) { 0
381 if (!BlockValueSet.insert(BV).second) 0
382 return false; // It's already in the stack. 0
383 ----
384 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "PUSH: " << *BV.second << " in " 0
385 << BV.first->getName() << "\n"); ----
386 BlockValueStack.push_back(BV); 0
387 return true; 0
388 } ----

484 ----
485 void LazyValueInfoImpl::solve() { 0
486 SmallVector, 8> StartingStack( ----
487 BlockValueStack.begin(), BlockValueStack.end()); 0
488 ----
489 unsigned processedCount = 0; 0
490 while (!BlockValueStack.empty()) { 0
491 processedCount++; 0
492 // Abort if we have to process too many values to get a result for this one. ----
493 // Because of the design of the overdefined cache currently being per-block ----
494 // to avoid naming-related issues (IE it wants to try to give different ----
495 // results for the same name in different blocks), overdefined results don't ----
496 // get cached globally, which in turn means we will often try to rediscover ----
497 // the same overdefined result again and again. Once something like ----
498 // PredicateInfo is used in LVI or CVP, we should be able to make the ----
499 // overdefined cache global, and remove this throttle. ----
500 if (processedCount > MaxProcessedPerValue) { 0
501 LLVM_DEBUG( 0
502 dbgs() << "Giving up on stack because we are getting too deep\n"); ----
503 // Fill in the original values ----
504 while (!StartingStack.empty()) { 0
505 std::pair &e = StartingStack.back(); 0
506 TheCache.insertResult(e.second, e.first, 0
507 ValueLatticeElement::getOverdefined()); 0
508 StartingStack.pop_back(); 0
509 } ----
510 BlockValueSet.clear(); 0
511 BlockValueStack.clear(); 0
512 return; 0
513 } ----
514 std::pair e = BlockValueStack.back(); 0
515 assert(BlockValueSet.count(e) && "Stack value should be in BlockValueSet!"); 0
516 ----
517 if (solveBlockValue(e.second, e.first)) { 0
518 // The work item was completely processed. ----
519 assert(BlockValueStack.back() == e && "Nothing should have been pushed!"); 0
520 #ifndef NDEBUG ----
521 std::optional BBLV = ----
522 TheCache.getCachedValueInfo(e.second, e.first); 0
523 assert(BBLV && "Result should be in cache!"); 0
524 LLVM_DEBUG( 0
525 dbgs() << "POP " << *e.second << " in " << e.first->getName() << " = " ----
526 << *BBLV << "\n"); ----
527 #endif ----
528 ----
529 BlockValueStack.pop_back(); 0
530 BlockValueSet.erase(e); 0
531 } else { 0
532 // More work needs to be done before revisiting. ----
533 assert(BlockValueStack.back() != e && "Stack should have been pushed!"); 0
534 } ----
535 } ----
536 } 0
537 ----
538 std::optional ----
539 LazyValueInfoImpl::getBlockValue(Value *Val, BasicBlock *BB, 0
540 Instruction *CxtI) { ----
541 // If already a constant, there is nothing to compute. ----
542 if (Constant *VC = dyn_cast(Val)) 0
543 return ValueLatticeElement::get(VC); 0
544 ----
545 if (std::optional OptLatticeVal = 0
546 TheCache.getCachedValueInfo(Val, BB)) { 0
547 intersectAssumeOrGuardBlockValueConstantRange(Val, *OptLatticeVal, CxtI); 0
548 return OptLatticeVal; 0
549 } 0
550 ----
551 // We have hit a cycle, assume overdefined. ----
552 if (!pushBlockValue({ BB, Val })) 0
553 return ValueLatticeElement::getOverdefined(); 0
554 ----
555 // Yet to be resolved. ----
556 return std::nullopt; 0
557 } ----
558 ----
559 static ValueLatticeElement getFromRangeMetadata(Instruction *BBI) { 0
560 switch (BBI->getOpcode()) { 0
561 default: break; 0
562 case Instruction::Load: 0
563 case Instruction::Call: ----
564 case Instruction::Invoke: ----
565 if (MDNode *Ranges = BBI->getMetadata(LLVMContext::MD_range)) 0
566 if (isa(BBI->getType())) { 0
567 return ValueLatticeElement::getRange( ----
568 getConstantRangeFromMetadata(*Ranges)); 0
569 } ----
570 break; 0
571 }; ----
572 // Nothing known - will be intersected with other facts ----
573 return ValueLatticeElement::getOverdefined(); 0
574 } ----
575 ----
576 bool LazyValueInfoImpl::solveBlockValue(Value *Val, BasicBlock *BB) { 0
577 assert(!isa(Val) && "Value should not be constant"); 0
578 assert(!TheCache.getCachedValueInfo(Val, BB) && 0
579 "Value should not be in cache"); ----
580 ----
581 // Hold off inserting this value into the Cache in case we have to return ----
582 // false and come back later. ----
583 std::optional Res = solveBlockValueImpl(Val, BB); 0
584 if (!Res) 0
585 // Work pushed, will revisit ----
586 return false; 0
587 ----
588 TheCache.insertResult(Val, BB, *Res); 0
589 return true; 0
590 } 0
591 ----
592 std::optional ----
593 LazyValueInfoImpl::solveBlockValueImpl(Value *Val, BasicBlock *BB) { 0
594 Instruction *BBI = dyn_cast(Val); 0
595 if (!BBI || BBI->getParent() != BB) 0
596 return solveBlockValueNonLocal(Val, BB); 0
597 ----
598 if (PHINode *PN = dyn_cast(BBI)) 0
599 return solveBlockValuePHINode(PN, BB); 0
600 ----
601 if (auto *SI = dyn_cast(BBI)) 0
602 return solveBlockValueSelect(SI, BB); 0
603 ----
604 // If this value is a nonnull pointer, record it's range and bailout. Note ----
605 // that for all other pointer typed values, we terminate the search at the ----
606 // definition. We could easily extend this to look through geps, bitcasts, ----
607 // and the like to prove non-nullness, but it's not clear that's worth it ----
608 // compile time wise. The context-insensitive value walk done inside ----
609 // isKnownNonZero gets most of the profitable cases at much less expense. ----
610 // This does mean that we have a sensitivity to where the defining ----
611 // instruction is placed, even if it could legally be hoisted much higher. ----
612 // That is unfortunate. ----
613 PointerType *PT = dyn_cast(BBI->getType()); 0
614 if (PT && isKnownNonZero(BBI, DL)) 0
615 return ValueLatticeElement::getNot(ConstantPointerNull::get(PT)); 0
616 ----
617 if (BBI->getType()->isIntegerTy()) { 0
618 if (auto *CI = dyn_cast(BBI)) 0
619 return solveBlockValueCast(CI, BB); 0
620 ----
621 if (BinaryOperator *BO = dyn_cast(BBI)) 0
622 return solveBlockValueBinaryOp(BO, BB); 0
623 ----
624 if (auto *EVI = dyn_cast(BBI)) 0
625 return solveBlockValueExtractValue(EVI, BB); 0
626 ----
627 if (auto *II = dyn_cast(BBI)) 0
628 return solveBlockValueIntrinsic(II, BB); 0
629 } ----
630 ----
631 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " compute BB '" << BB->getName() 0
632 << "' - unknown inst def found.\n"); ----
633 return getFromRangeMetadata(BBI); 0
634 } ----
635 ----
636 static void AddNonNullPointer(Value *Ptr, NonNullPointerSet &PtrSet) { 0
637 // TODO: Use NullPointerIsDefined instead. ----
638 if (Ptr->getType()->getPointerAddressSpace() == 0) 0
639 PtrSet.insert(getUnderlyingObject(Ptr)); 0
640 } 0
641 ----
642 static void AddNonNullPointersByInstruction( 0
643 Instruction *I, NonNullPointerSet &PtrSet) { ----
644 if (LoadInst *L = dyn_cast(I)) { 0
645 AddNonNullPointer(L->getPointerOperand(), PtrSet); 0
646 } else if (StoreInst *S = dyn_cast(I)) { 0
647 AddNonNullPointer(S->getPointerOperand(), PtrSet); 0
648 } else if (MemIntrinsic *MI = dyn_cast(I)) { 0
649 if (MI->isVolatile()) return; 0
650 ----
651 // FIXME: check whether it has a valuerange that excludes zero? ----
652 ConstantInt *Len = dyn_cast(MI->getLength()); 0
653 if (!Len || Len->isZero()) return; 0
654 ----
655 AddNonNullPointer(MI->getRawDest(), PtrSet); 0
656 if (MemTransferInst *MTI = dyn_cast(MI)) 0
657 AddNonNullPointer(MTI->getRawSource(), PtrSet); 0
658 } ----
659 } ----
660 ----
661 bool LazyValueInfoImpl::isNonNullAtEndOfBlock(Value *Val, BasicBlock *BB) { 0
662 if (NullPointerIsDefined(BB->getParent(), 0
663 Val->getType()->getPointerAddressSpace())) ----
664 return false; 0
665 ----
666 Val = Val->stripInBoundsOffsets(); 0
667 return TheCache.isNonNullAtEndOfBlock(Val, BB, [](BasicBlock *BB) { 0
668 NonNullPointerSet NonNullPointers; 0
669 for (Instruction &I : *BB) 0
670 AddNonNullPointersByInstruction(&I, NonNullPointers); 0
671 return NonNullPointers; 0
672 }); 0
673 } ----
674 ----
675 std::optional ----
676 LazyValueInfoImpl::solveBlockValueNonLocal(Value *Val, BasicBlock *BB) { 0
677 ValueLatticeElement Result; // Start Undefined. 0
678 ----
679 // If this is the entry block, we must be asking about an argument. The ----
680 // value is overdefined. ----
681 if (BB->isEntryBlock()) { 0
682 assert(isa(Val) && "Unknown live-in to the entry block"); 0
683 return ValueLatticeElement::getOverdefined(); 0
684 } ----
685 ----
686 // Loop over all of our predecessors, merging what we know from them into ----
687 // result. If we encounter an unexplored predecessor, we eagerly explore it ----
688 // in a depth first manner. In practice, this has the effect of discovering ----
689 // paths we can't analyze eagerly without spending compile times analyzing ----
690 // other paths. This heuristic benefits from the fact that predecessors are ----
691 // frequently arranged such that dominating ones come first and we quickly ----
692 // find a path to function entry. TODO: We should consider explicitly ----
693 // canonicalizing to make this true rather than relying on this happy ----
694 // accident. ----
695 for (BasicBlock *Pred : predecessors(BB)) { 0
696 std::optional EdgeResult = getEdgeValue(Val, Pred, BB); 0
697 if (!EdgeResult) 0
698 // Explore that input, then return here ----
699 return std::nullopt; 0
700 ----
701 Result.mergeIn(*EdgeResult); 0
702 ----
703 // If we hit overdefined, exit early. The BlockVals entry is already set ----
704 // to overdefined. ----
705 if (Result.isOverdefined()) { 0
706 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " compute BB '" << BB->getName() 0
707 << "' - overdefined because of pred '" ----
708 << Pred->getName() << "' (non local).\n"); ----
709 return Result; 0
710 } ----
711 } 0
712 ----
713 // Return the merged value, which is more precise than 'overdefined'. ----
714 assert(!Result.isOverdefined()); 0
715 return Result; 0
716 } 0
717 ----
718 std::optional ----
719 LazyValueInfoImpl::solveBlockValuePHINode(PHINode *PN, BasicBlock *BB) { 0
720 ValueLatticeElement Result; // Start Undefined. 0
721 ----
722 // Loop over all of our predecessors, merging what we know from them into ----
723 // result. See the comment about the chosen traversal order in ----
724 // solveBlockValueNonLocal; the same reasoning applies here. ----
725 for (unsigned i = 0, e = PN->getNumIncomingValues(); i != e; ++i) { 0
726 BasicBlock *PhiBB = PN->getIncomingBlock(i); 0
727 Value *PhiVal = PN->getIncomingValue(i); 0
728 // Note that we can provide PN as the context value to getEdgeValue, even ----
729 // though the results will be cached, because PN is the value being used as ----
730 // the cache key in the caller. ----
731 std::optional EdgeResult = ----
732 getEdgeValue(PhiVal, PhiBB, BB, PN); 0
733 if (!EdgeResult) 0
734 // Explore that input, then return here ----
735 return std::nullopt; 0
736 ----
737 Result.mergeIn(*EdgeResult); 0
738 ----
739 // If we hit overdefined, exit early. The BlockVals entry is already set ----
740 // to overdefined. ----
741 if (Result.isOverdefined()) { 0
742 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " compute BB '" << BB->getName() 0
743 << "' - overdefined because of pred (local).\n"); ----
744 ----
745 return Result; 0
746 } ----
747 } 0
748 ----
749 // Return the merged value, which is more precise than 'overdefined'. ----
750 assert(!Result.isOverdefined() && "Possible PHI in entry block?"); 0
751 return Result; 0
752 } 0
753 ----
754 static ValueLatticeElement getValueFromCondition(Value *Val, Value *Cond, ----
755 bool isTrueDest = true); ----
756 ----
757 // If we can determine a constraint on the value given conditions assumed by ----
758 // the program, intersect those constraints with BBLV ----
759 void LazyValueInfoImpl::intersectAssumeOrGuardBlockValueConstantRange( 0
760 Value *Val, ValueLatticeElement &BBLV, Instruction *BBI) { ----
761 BBI = BBI ? BBI : dyn_cast(Val); 0
762 if (!BBI) 0
763 return; 0
764 ----
765 BasicBlock *BB = BBI->getParent(); 0
766 for (auto &AssumeVH : AC->assumptionsFor(Val)) { 0
767 if (!AssumeVH) 0
768 continue; 0
769 ----
770 // Only check assumes in the block of the context instruction. Other ----
771 // assumes will have already been taken into account when the value was ----
772 // propagated from predecessor blocks. ----
773 auto *I = cast(AssumeVH); 0
774 if (I->getParent() != BB || !isValidAssumeForContext(I, BBI)) 0
775 continue; 0
776 ----
777 BBLV = intersect(BBLV, getValueFromCondition(Val, I->getArgOperand(0))); 0
778 } ----
779 ----
780 // If guards are not used in the module, don't spend time looking for them ----
781 if (GuardDecl && !GuardDecl->use_empty() && 0
782 BBI->getIterator() != BB->begin()) { 0
783 for (Instruction &I : make_range(std::next(BBI->getIterator().getReverse()), 0
784 BB->rend())) { 0
785 Value *Cond = nullptr; 0
786 if (match(&I, m_Intrinsic(m_Value(Cond)))) 0
787 BBLV = intersect(BBLV, getValueFromCondition(Val, Cond)); 0
788 } ----
789 } ----
790 ----
791 if (BBLV.isOverdefined()) { 0
792 // Check whether we're checking at the terminator, and the pointer has ----
793 // been dereferenced in this block. ----
794 PointerType *PTy = dyn_cast(Val->getType()); 0
795 if (PTy && BB->getTerminator() == BBI && 0
796 isNonNullAtEndOfBlock(Val, BB)) 0
797 BBLV = ValueLatticeElement::getNot(ConstantPointerNull::get(PTy)); 0
798 } ----
799 } ----
800 ----
801 static ConstantRange getConstantRangeOrFull(const ValueLatticeElement &Val, 0
802 Type *Ty, const DataLayout &DL) { ----
803 if (Val.isConstantRange()) 0
804 return Val.getConstantRange(); 0
805 return ConstantRange::getFull(DL.getTypeSizeInBits(Ty)); 0
806 } ----
807 ----
808 std::optional ----
809 LazyValueInfoImpl::solveBlockValueSelect(SelectInst *SI, BasicBlock *BB) { 0
810 // Recurse on our inputs if needed ----
811 std::optional OptTrueVal = ----
812 getBlockValue(SI->getTrueValue(), BB, SI); 0
813 if (!OptTrueVal) 0
814 return std::nullopt; 0
815 ValueLatticeElement &TrueVal = *OptTrueVal; 0
816 ----
817 std::optional OptFalseVal = ----
818 getBlockValue(SI->getFalseValue(), BB, SI); 0
819 if (!OptFalseVal) 0
820 return std::nullopt; 0
821 ValueLatticeElement &FalseVal = *OptFalseVal; 0
822 ----
823 if (TrueVal.isConstantRange() || FalseVal.isConstantRange()) { 0
824 const ConstantRange &TrueCR = ----
825 getConstantRangeOrFull(TrueVal, SI->getType(), DL); 0
826 const ConstantRange &FalseCR = ----
827 getConstantRangeOrFull(FalseVal, SI->getType(), DL); 0
828 Value *LHS = nullptr; 0
829 Value *RHS = nullptr; 0
830 SelectPatternResult SPR = matchSelectPattern(SI, LHS, RHS); 0
831 // Is this a min specifically of our two inputs? (Avoid the risk of ----
832 // ValueTracking getting smarter looking back past our immediate inputs.) ----
833 if (SelectPatternResult::isMinOrMax(SPR.Flavor) && 0
834 ((LHS == SI->getTrueValue() && RHS == SI->getFalseValue()) || 0
835 (RHS == SI->getTrueValue() && LHS == SI->getFalseValue()))) { 0
836 ConstantRange ResultCR = [&]() { 0
837 switch (SPR.Flavor) { 0
838 default: 0
839 llvm_unreachable("unexpected minmax type!"); 0
840 case SPF_SMIN: /// Signed minimum 0
841 return TrueCR.smin(FalseCR); 0
842 case SPF_UMIN: /// Unsigned minimum 0
843 return TrueCR.umin(FalseCR); 0
844 case SPF_SMAX: /// Signed maximum 0
845 return TrueCR.smax(FalseCR); 0
846 case SPF_UMAX: /// Unsigned maximum 0
847 return TrueCR.umax(FalseCR); 0
848 }; ----
849 }(); 0
850 return ValueLatticeElement::getRange( 0
851 ResultCR, TrueVal.isConstantRangeIncludingUndef() || 0
852 FalseVal.isConstantRangeIncludingUndef()); 0
853 } 0
854 ----
855 if (SPR.Flavor == SPF_ABS) { 0
856 if (LHS == SI->getTrueValue()) 0
857 return ValueLatticeElement::getRange( 0
858 TrueCR.abs(), TrueVal.isConstantRangeIncludingUndef()); 0
859 if (LHS == SI->getFalseValue()) 0
860 return ValueLatticeElement::getRange( 0
861 FalseCR.abs(), FalseVal.isConstantRangeIncludingUndef()); 0
862 } ----
863 ----
864 if (SPR.Flavor == SPF_NABS) { 0
865 ConstantRange Zero(APInt::getZero(TrueCR.getBitWidth())); 0
866 if (LHS == SI->getTrueValue()) 0
867 return ValueLatticeElement::getRange( 0
868 Zero.sub(TrueCR.abs()), FalseVal.isConstantRangeIncludingUndef()); 0
869 if (LHS == SI->getFalseValue()) 0
870 return ValueLatticeElement::getRange( 0
871 Zero.sub(FalseCR.abs()), FalseVal.isConstantRangeIncludingUndef()); 0
872 } 0
873 } 0
874 ----
875 // Can we constrain the facts about the true and false values by using the ----
876 // condition itself? This shows up with idioms like e.g. select(a > 5, a, 5). ----
877 // TODO: We could potentially refine an overdefined true value above. ----
878 Value *Cond = SI->getCondition(); 0
879 // If the value is undef, a different value may be chosen in ----
880 // the select condition. ----
881 if (isGuaranteedNotToBeUndefOrPoison(Cond, AC)) { 0
882 TrueVal = intersect(TrueVal, 0
883 getValueFromCondition(SI->getTrueValue(), Cond, true)); 0
884 FalseVal = intersect( 0
885 FalseVal, getValueFromCondition(SI->getFalseValue(), Cond, false)); 0
886 } ----
887 ----
888 ValueLatticeElement Result = TrueVal; 0
889 Result.mergeIn(FalseVal); 0
890 return Result; 0
891 } 0
892 ----
893 std::optional ----
894 LazyValueInfoImpl::getRangeFor(Value *V, Instruction *CxtI, BasicBlock *BB) { 0
895 std::optional OptVal = getBlockValue(V, BB, CxtI); 0
896 if (!OptVal) 0
897 return std::nullopt; 0
898 return getConstantRangeOrFull(*OptVal, V->getType(), DL); 0
899 } 0
900 ----
901 std::optional ----
902 LazyValueInfoImpl::solveBlockValueCast(CastInst *CI, BasicBlock *BB) { 0
903 // Without knowing how wide the input is, we can't analyze it in any useful ----
904 // way. ----
905 if (!CI->getOperand(0)->getType()->isSized()) 0
906 return ValueLatticeElement::getOverdefined(); 0
907 ----
908 // Filter out casts we don't know how to reason about before attempting to ----
909 // recurse on our operand. This can cut a long search short if we know we're ----
910 // not going to be able to get any useful information anways. ----
911 switch (CI->getOpcode()) { 0
912 case Instruction::Trunc: 0
913 case Instruction::SExt: ----
914 case Instruction::ZExt: ----
915 case Instruction::BitCast: ----
916 break; 0
917 default: 0
918 // Unhandled instructions are overdefined. ----
919 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " compute BB '" << BB->getName() 0
920 << "' - overdefined (unknown cast).\n"); ----
921 return ValueLatticeElement::getOverdefined(); 0
922 } ----
923 ----
924 // Figure out the range of the LHS. If that fails, we still apply the ----
925 // transfer rule on the full set since we may be able to locally infer ----
926 // interesting facts. ----
927 std::optional LHSRes = getRangeFor(CI->getOperand(0), CI, BB); 0
928 if (!LHSRes) 0
929 // More work to do before applying this transfer rule. ----
930 return std::nullopt; 0
931 const ConstantRange &LHSRange = *LHSRes; 0
932 ----
933 const unsigned ResultBitWidth = CI->getType()->getIntegerBitWidth(); 0
934 ----
935 // NOTE: We're currently limited by the set of operations that ConstantRange ----
936 // can evaluate symbolically. Enhancing that set will allows us to analyze ----
937 // more definitions. ----
938 return ValueLatticeElement::getRange(LHSRange.castOp(CI->getOpcode(), 0
939 ResultBitWidth)); 0
940 } ----
941 ----
942 std::optional ----
943 LazyValueInfoImpl::solveBlockValueBinaryOpImpl( 0
944 Instruction *I, BasicBlock *BB, ----
945 std::function ----
946 OpFn) { ----
947 // Figure out the ranges of the operands. If that fails, use a ----
948 // conservative range, but apply the transfer rule anyways. This ----
949 // lets us pick up facts from expressions like "and i32 (call i32 ----
950 // @foo()), 32" ----
951 std::optional LHSRes = getRangeFor(I->getOperand(0), I, BB); 0
952 std::optional RHSRes = getRangeFor(I->getOperand(1), I, BB); 0
953 if (!LHSRes || !RHSRes) 0
954 // More work to do before applying this transfer rule. ----
955 return std::nullopt; 0
956 ----
957 const ConstantRange &LHSRange = *LHSRes; 0
958 const ConstantRange &RHSRange = *RHSRes; 0
959 return ValueLatticeElement::getRange(OpFn(LHSRange, RHSRange)); 0
960 } 0
961 ----
962 std::optional ----
963 LazyValueInfoImpl::solveBlockValueBinaryOp(BinaryOperator *BO, BasicBlock *BB) { 0
964 assert(BO->getOperand(0)->getType()->isSized() && 0
965 "all operands to binary operators are sized"); ----
966 if (auto *OBO = dyn_cast(BO)) { 0
967 unsigned NoWrapKind = 0; 0
968 if (OBO->hasNoUnsignedWrap()) 0
969 NoWrapKind |= OverflowingBinaryOperator::NoUnsignedWrap; 0
970 if (OBO->hasNoSignedWrap()) 0
971 NoWrapKind |= OverflowingBinaryOperator::NoSignedWrap; 0
972 ----
973 return solveBlockValueBinaryOpImpl( ----
974 BO, BB, ----
975 [BO, NoWrapKind](const ConstantRange &CR1, const ConstantRange &CR2) { 0
976 return CR1.overflowingBinaryOp(BO->getOpcode(), CR2, NoWrapKind); 0
977 }); 0
978 } ----
979 ----
980 return solveBlockValueBinaryOpImpl( ----
981 BO, BB, [BO](const ConstantRange &CR1, const ConstantRange &CR2) { 0
982 return CR1.binaryOp(BO->getOpcode(), CR2); 0
983 }); 0
984 } ----
985 ----
986 std::optional ----
987 LazyValueInfoImpl::solveBlockValueOverflowIntrinsic(WithOverflowInst *WO, 0
988 BasicBlock *BB) { ----
989 return solveBlockValueBinaryOpImpl( ----
990 WO, BB, [WO](const ConstantRange &CR1, const ConstantRange &CR2) { 0
991 return CR1.binaryOp(WO->getBinaryOp(), CR2); 0
992 }); 0
993 } ----
994 ----
995 std::optional ----
996 LazyValueInfoImpl::solveBlockValueIntrinsic(IntrinsicInst *II, BasicBlock *BB) { 0
997 ValueLatticeElement MetadataVal = getFromRangeMetadata(II); 0
998 if (!ConstantRange::isIntrinsicSupported(II->getIntrinsicID())) { 0
999 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " compute BB '" << BB->getName() 0
1000 << "' - unknown intrinsic.\n"); ----
1001 return MetadataVal; 0
1002 } ----
1003 ----
1004 SmallVector OpRanges; 0
1005 for (Value *Op : II->args()) { 0
1006 std::optional Range = getRangeFor(Op, II, BB); 0
1007 if (!Range) 0
1008 return std::nullopt; 0
1009 OpRanges.push_back(*Range); 0
1010 } 0
1011 ----
1012 return intersect(ValueLatticeElement::getRange(ConstantRange::intrinsic( 0
1013 II->getIntrinsicID(), OpRanges)), ----
1014 MetadataVal); 0
1015 } 0
1016 ----
1017 std::optional ----
1018 LazyValueInfoImpl::solveBlockValueExtractValue(ExtractValueInst *EVI, 0
1019 BasicBlock *BB) { ----
1020 if (auto *WO = dyn_cast(EVI->getAggregateOperand())) 0
1021 if (EVI->getNumIndices() == 1 && *EVI->idx_begin() == 0) 0
1022 return solveBlockValueOverflowIntrinsic(WO, BB); 0
1023 ----
1024 // Handle extractvalue of insertvalue to allow further simplification ----
1025 // based on replaced with.overflow intrinsics. ----
1026 if (Value *V = simplifyExtractValueInst( 0
1027 EVI->getAggregateOperand(), EVI->getIndices(), ----
1028 EVI->getModule()->getDataLayout())) ----
1029 return getBlockValue(V, BB, EVI); 0
1030 ----
1031 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " compute BB '" << BB->getName() 0
1032 << "' - overdefined (unknown extractvalue).\n"); ----
1033 return ValueLatticeElement::getOverdefined(); 0
1034 } ----
1035 ----
1036 static bool matchICmpOperand(APInt &Offset, Value *LHS, Value *Val, 0
1037 ICmpInst::Predicate Pred) { ----
1038 if (LHS == Val) 0
1039 return true; 0
1040 ----
1041 // Handle range checking idiom produced by InstCombine. We will subtract the ----
1042 // offset from the allowed range for RHS in this case. ----
1043 const APInt *C; ----
1044 if (match(LHS, m_Add(m_Specific(Val), m_APInt(C)))) { 0
1045 Offset = *C; 0
1046 return true; 0
1047 } ----
1048 ----
1049 // Handle the symmetric case. This appears in saturation patterns like ----
1050 // (x == 16) ? 16 : (x + 1). ----
1051 if (match(Val, m_Add(m_Specific(LHS), m_APInt(C)))) { 0
1052 Offset = -*C; 0
1053 return true; 0
1054 } ----
1055 ----
1056 // If (x | y) < C, then (x < C) && (y < C). ----
1057 if (match(LHS, m_c_Or(m_Specific(Val), m_Value())) && 0
1058 (Pred == ICmpInst::ICMP_ULT || Pred == ICmpInst::ICMP_ULE)) 0
1059 return true; 0
1060 ----
1061 // If (x & y) > C, then (x > C) && (y > C). ----
1062 if (match(LHS, m_c_And(m_Specific(Val), m_Value())) && 0
1063 (Pred == ICmpInst::ICMP_UGT || Pred == ICmpInst::ICMP_UGE)) 0
1064 return true; 0
1065 ----
1066 return false; 0
1067 } ----
1068 ----
1069 /// Get value range for a "(Val + Offset) Pred RHS" condition. ----
1070 static ValueLatticeElement getValueFromSimpleICmpCondition( 0
1071 CmpInst::Predicate Pred, Value *RHS, const APInt &Offset) { ----
1072 ConstantRange RHSRange(RHS->getType()->getIntegerBitWidth(), ----
1073 /*isFullSet=*/true); 0
1074 if (ConstantInt *CI = dyn_cast(RHS)) 0
1075 RHSRange = ConstantRange(CI->getValue()); 0
1076 else if (Instruction *I = dyn_cast(RHS)) 0
1077 if (auto *Ranges = I->getMetadata(LLVMContext::MD_range)) 0
1078 RHSRange = getConstantRangeFromMetadata(*Ranges); 0
1079 ----
1080 ConstantRange TrueValues = ----
1081 ConstantRange::makeAllowedICmpRegion(Pred, RHSRange); 0
1082 return ValueLatticeElement::getRange(TrueValues.subtract(Offset)); 0
1083 } 0
1084 ----
1085 static ValueLatticeElement getValueFromICmpCondition(Value *Val, ICmpInst *ICI, 0
1086 bool isTrueDest) { ----
1087 Value *LHS = ICI->getOperand(0); 0
1088 Value *RHS = ICI->getOperand(1); 0
1089 ----
1090 // Get the predicate that must hold along the considered edge. ----
1091 CmpInst::Predicate EdgePred = ----
1092 isTrueDest ? ICI->getPredicate() : ICI->getInversePredicate(); 0
1093 ----
1094 if (isa(RHS)) { 0
1095 if (ICI->isEquality() && LHS == Val) { 0
1096 if (EdgePred == ICmpInst::ICMP_EQ) 0
1097 return ValueLatticeElement::get(cast(RHS)); 0
1098 else if (!isa(RHS)) 0
1099 return ValueLatticeElement::getNot(cast(RHS)); 0
1100 } ----
1101 } ----
1102 ----
1103 Type *Ty = Val->getType(); 0
1104 if (!Ty->isIntegerTy()) 0
1105 return ValueLatticeElement::getOverdefined(); 0
1106 ----
1107 unsigned BitWidth = Ty->getScalarSizeInBits(); 0
1108 APInt Offset(BitWidth, 0); 0
1109 if (matchICmpOperand(Offset, LHS, Val, EdgePred)) 0
1110 return getValueFromSimpleICmpCondition(EdgePred, RHS, Offset); 0
1111 ----
1112 CmpInst::Predicate SwappedPred = CmpInst::getSwappedPredicate(EdgePred); 0
1113 if (matchICmpOperand(Offset, RHS, Val, SwappedPred)) 0
1114 return getValueFromSimpleICmpCondition(SwappedPred, LHS, Offset); 0
1115 ----
1116 const APInt *Mask, *C; ----
1117 if (match(LHS, m_And(m_Specific(Val), m_APInt(Mask))) && 0
1118 match(RHS, m_APInt(C))) { 0
1119 // If (Val & Mask) == C then all the masked bits are known and we can ----
1120 // compute a value range based on that. ----
1121 if (EdgePred == ICmpInst::ICMP_EQ) { 0
1122 KnownBits Known; 0
1123 Known.Zero = ~*C & *Mask; 0
1124 Known.One = *C & *Mask; 0
1125 return ValueLatticeElement::getRange( ----
1126 ConstantRange::fromKnownBits(Known, /*IsSigned*/ false)); 0
1127 } 0
1128 // If (Val & Mask) != 0 then the value must be larger than the lowest set ----
1129 // bit of Mask. ----
1130 if (EdgePred == ICmpInst::ICMP_NE && !Mask->isZero() && C->isZero()) { 0
1131 return ValueLatticeElement::getRange(ConstantRange::getNonEmpty( 0
1132 APInt::getOneBitSet(BitWidth, Mask->countr_zero()), 0
1133 APInt::getZero(BitWidth))); 0
1134 } ----
1135 } ----
1136 ----
1137 // If (X urem Modulus) >= C, then X >= C. ----
1138 // If trunc X >= C, then X >= C. ----
1139 // TODO: An upper bound could be computed as well. ----
1140 if (match(LHS, m_CombineOr(m_URem(m_Specific(Val), m_Value()), 0
1141 m_Trunc(m_Specific(Val)))) && 0
1142 match(RHS, m_APInt(C))) { 0
1143 // Use the icmp region so we don't have to deal with different predicates. ----
1144 ConstantRange CR = ConstantRange::makeExactICmpRegion(EdgePred, *C); 0
1145 if (!CR.isEmptySet()) 0
1146 return ValueLatticeElement::getRange(ConstantRange::getNonEmpty( 0
1147 CR.getUnsignedMin().zext(BitWidth), APInt(BitWidth, 0))); 0
1148 } 0
1149 ----
1150 return ValueLatticeElement::getOverdefined(); 0
1151 } 0
1152 ----
1153 // Handle conditions of the form ----
1154 // extractvalue(op.with.overflow(%x, C), 1). ----
1155 static ValueLatticeElement getValueFromOverflowCondition( 0
1156 Value *Val, WithOverflowInst *WO, bool IsTrueDest) { ----
1157 // TODO: This only works with a constant RHS for now. We could also compute ----
1158 // the range of the RHS, but this doesn't fit into the current structure of ----
1159 // the edge value calculation. ----
1160 const APInt *C; ----
1161 if (WO->getLHS() != Val || !match(WO->getRHS(), m_APInt(C))) 0
1162 return ValueLatticeElement::getOverdefined(); 0
1163 ----
1164 // Calculate the possible values of %x for which no overflow occurs. ----
1165 ConstantRange NWR = ConstantRange::makeExactNoWrapRegion( ----
1166 WO->getBinaryOp(), *C, WO->getNoWrapKind()); 0
1167 ----
1168 // If overflow is false, %x is constrained to NWR. If overflow is true, %x is ----
1169 // constrained to it's inverse (all values that might cause overflow). ----
1170 if (IsTrueDest) 0
1171 NWR = NWR.inverse(); 0
1172 return ValueLatticeElement::getRange(NWR); 0
1173 } 0
1174 ----
1175 // Tracks a Value * condition and whether we're interested in it or its inverse ----
1176 typedef PointerIntPair CondValue; ----
1177 ----
1178 static std::optional getValueFromConditionImpl( 0
1179 Value *Val, CondValue CondVal, bool isRevisit, ----
1180 SmallDenseMap &Visited, ----
1181 SmallVectorImpl &Worklist) { ----
1182 ----
1183 Value *Cond = CondVal.getPointer(); 0
1184 bool isTrueDest = CondVal.getInt(); 0
1185 if (!isRevisit) { 0
1186 if (ICmpInst *ICI = dyn_cast(Cond)) 0
1187 return getValueFromICmpCondition(Val, ICI, isTrueDest); 0
1188 ----
1189 if (auto *EVI = dyn_cast(Cond)) 0
1190 if (auto *WO = dyn_cast(EVI->getAggregateOperand())) 0
1191 if (EVI->getNumIndices() == 1 && *EVI->idx_begin() == 1) 0
1192 return getValueFromOverflowCondition(Val, WO, isTrueDest); 0
1193 } ----
1194 ----
1195 Value *N; ----
1196 if (match(Cond, m_Not(m_Value(N)))) { 0
1197 CondValue NKey(N, !isTrueDest); 0
1198 auto NV = Visited.find(NKey); 0
1199 if (NV == Visited.end()) { 0
1200 Worklist.push_back(NKey); 0
1201 return std::nullopt; 0
1202 } ----
1203 return NV->second; 0
1204 } ----
1205 ----
1206 Value *L, *R; ----
1207 bool IsAnd; ----
1208 if (match(Cond, m_LogicalAnd(m_Value(L), m_Value(R)))) 0
1209 IsAnd = true; 0
1210 else if (match(Cond, m_LogicalOr(m_Value(L), m_Value(R)))) 0
1211 IsAnd = false; 0
1212 else ----
1213 return ValueLatticeElement::getOverdefined(); 0
1214 ----
1215 auto LV = Visited.find(CondValue(L, isTrueDest)); 0
1216 auto RV = Visited.find(CondValue(R, isTrueDest)); 0
1217 ----
1218 // if (L && R) -> intersect L and R ----
1219 // if (!(L || R)) -> intersect !L and !R ----
1220 // if (L || R) -> union L and R ----
1221 // if (!(L && R)) -> union !L and !R ----
1222 if ((isTrueDest ^ IsAnd) && (LV != Visited.end())) { 0
1223 ValueLatticeElement V = LV->second; 0
1224 if (V.isOverdefined()) 0
1225 return V; 0
1226 if (RV != Visited.end()) { 0
1227 V.mergeIn(RV->second); 0
1228 return V; 0
1229 } ----
1230 } 0
1231 ----
1232 if (LV == Visited.end() || RV == Visited.end()) { 0
1233 assert(!isRevisit); 0
1234 if (LV == Visited.end()) 0
1235 Worklist.push_back(CondValue(L, isTrueDest)); 0
1236 if (RV == Visited.end()) 0
1237 Worklist.push_back(CondValue(R, isTrueDest)); 0
1238 return std::nullopt; 0
1239 } ----
1240 ----
1241 return intersect(LV->second, RV->second); 0
1242 } ----
1243 ----
1244 ValueLatticeElement getValueFromCondition(Value *Val, Value *Cond, 0
1245 bool isTrueDest) { ----
1246 assert(Cond && "precondition"); 0
1247 SmallDenseMap Visited; 0
1248 SmallVector Worklist; 0
1249 ----
1250 CondValue CondKey(Cond, isTrueDest); 0
1251 Worklist.push_back(CondKey); 0
1252 do { ----
1253 CondValue CurrentCond = Worklist.back(); 0
1254 // Insert an Overdefined placeholder into the set to prevent ----
1255 // infinite recursion if there exists IRs that use not ----
1256 // dominated by its def as in this example: ----
1257 // "%tmp3 = or i1 undef, %tmp4" ----
1258 // "%tmp4 = or i1 undef, %tmp3" ----
1259 auto Iter = ----
1260 Visited.try_emplace(CurrentCond, ValueLatticeElement::getOverdefined()); 0
1261 bool isRevisit = !Iter.second; 0
1262 std::optional Result = getValueFromConditionImpl( ----
1263 Val, CurrentCond, isRevisit, Visited, Worklist); 0
1264 if (Result) { 0
1265 Visited[CurrentCond] = *Result; 0
1266 Worklist.pop_back(); 0
1267 } ----
1268 } while (!Worklist.empty()); 0
1269 ----
1270 auto Result = Visited.find(CondKey); 0
1271 assert(Result != Visited.end()); 0
1272 return Result->second; 0
1273 } 0
1274 ----
1275 // Return true if Usr has Op as an operand, otherwise false. ----
1276 static bool usesOperand(User *Usr, Value *Op) { 0
1277 return is_contained(Usr->operands(), Op); 0
1278 } ----
1279 ----
1280 // Return true if the instruction type of Val is supported by ----
1281 // constantFoldUser(). Currently CastInst, BinaryOperator and FreezeInst only. ----
1282 // Call this before calling constantFoldUser() to find out if it's even worth ----
1283 // attempting to call it. ----
1284 static bool isOperationFoldable(User *Usr) { 0
1285 return isa(Usr) || isa(Usr) || isa(Usr); 0
1286 } ----
1287 ----
1288 // Check if Usr can be simplified to an integer constant when the value of one ----
1289 // of its operands Op is an integer constant OpConstVal. If so, return it as an ----
1290 // lattice value range with a single element or otherwise return an overdefined ----
1291 // lattice value. ----
1292 static ValueLatticeElement constantFoldUser(User *Usr, Value *Op, 0
1293 const APInt &OpConstVal, ----
1294 const DataLayout &DL) { ----
1295 assert(isOperationFoldable(Usr) && "Precondition"); 0
1296 Constant* OpConst = Constant::getIntegerValue(Op->getType(), OpConstVal); 0
1297 // Check if Usr can be simplified to a constant. ----
1298 if (auto *CI = dyn_cast(Usr)) { 0
1299 assert(CI->getOperand(0) == Op && "Operand 0 isn't Op"); 0
1300 if (auto *C = dyn_cast_or_null( 0
1301 simplifyCastInst(CI->getOpcode(), OpConst, 0
1302 CI->getDestTy(), DL))) { ----
1303 return ValueLatticeElement::getRange(ConstantRange(C->getValue())); 0
1304 } ----
1305 } else if (auto *BO = dyn_cast(Usr)) { 0
1306 bool Op0Match = BO->getOperand(0) == Op; 0
1307 bool Op1Match = BO->getOperand(1) == Op; 0
1308 assert((Op0Match || Op1Match) && 0
1309 "Operand 0 nor Operand 1 isn't a match"); ----
1310 Value *LHS = Op0Match ? OpConst : BO->getOperand(0); 0
1311 Value *RHS = Op1Match ? OpConst : BO->getOperand(1); 0
1312 if (auto *C = dyn_cast_or_null( 0
1313 simplifyBinOp(BO->getOpcode(), LHS, RHS, DL))) { 0
1314 return ValueLatticeElement::getRange(ConstantRange(C->getValue())); 0
1315 } ----
1316 } else if (isa(Usr)) { 0
1317 assert(cast(Usr)->getOperand(0) == Op && "Operand 0 isn't Op"); 0
1318 return ValueLatticeElement::getRange(ConstantRange(OpConstVal)); 0
1319 } ----
1320 return ValueLatticeElement::getOverdefined(); 0
1321 } ----
1322 ----
1323 /// Compute the value of Val on the edge BBFrom -> BBTo. Returns false if ----
1324 /// Val is not constrained on the edge. Result is unspecified if return value ----
1325 /// is false. ----
1326 static std::optional getEdgeValueLocal(Value *Val, 0
1327 BasicBlock *BBFrom, ----
1328 BasicBlock *BBTo) { ----
1329 // TODO: Handle more complex conditionals. If (v == 0 || v2 < 1) is false, we ----
1330 // know that v != 0. ----
1331 if (BranchInst *BI = dyn_cast(BBFrom->getTerminator())) { 0
1332 // If this is a conditional branch and only one successor goes to BBTo, then ----
1333 // we may be able to infer something from the condition. ----
1334 if (BI->isConditional() && 0
1335 BI->getSuccessor(0) != BI->getSuccessor(1)) { 0
1336 bool isTrueDest = BI->getSuccessor(0) == BBTo; 0
1337 assert(BI->getSuccessor(!isTrueDest) == BBTo && 0
1338 "BBTo isn't a successor of BBFrom"); ----
1339 Value *Condition = BI->getCondition(); 0
1340 ----
1341 // If V is the condition of the branch itself, then we know exactly what ----
1342 // it is. ----
1343 if (Condition == Val) 0
1344 return ValueLatticeElement::get(ConstantInt::get( 0
1345 Type::getInt1Ty(Val->getContext()), isTrueDest)); 0
1346 ----
1347 // If the condition of the branch is an equality comparison, we may be ----
1348 // able to infer the value. ----
1349 ValueLatticeElement Result = getValueFromCondition(Val, Condition, ----
1350 isTrueDest); 0
1351 if (!Result.isOverdefined()) 0
1352 return Result; 0
1353 ----
1354 if (User *Usr = dyn_cast(Val)) { 0
1355 assert(Result.isOverdefined() && "Result isn't overdefined"); 0
1356 // Check with isOperationFoldable() first to avoid linearly iterating ----
1357 // over the operands unnecessarily which can be expensive for ----
1358 // instructions with many operands. ----
1359 if (isa(Usr->getType()) && isOperationFoldable(Usr)) { 0
1360 const DataLayout &DL = BBTo->getModule()->getDataLayout(); 0
1361 if (usesOperand(Usr, Condition)) { 0
1362 // If Val has Condition as an operand and Val can be folded into a ----
1363 // constant with either Condition == true or Condition == false, ----
1364 // propagate the constant. ----
1365 // eg. ----
1366 // ; %Val is true on the edge to %then. ----
1367 // %Val = and i1 %Condition, true. ----
1368 // br %Condition, label %then, label %else ----
1369 APInt ConditionVal(1, isTrueDest ? 1 : 0); 0
1370 Result = constantFoldUser(Usr, Condition, ConditionVal, DL); 0
1371 } else { 0
1372 // If one of Val's operand has an inferred value, we may be able to ----
1373 // infer the value of Val. ----
1374 // eg. ----
1375 // ; %Val is 94 on the edge to %then. ----
1376 // %Val = add i8 %Op, 1 ----
1377 // %Condition = icmp eq i8 %Op, 93 ----
1378 // br i1 %Condition, label %then, label %else ----
1379 for (unsigned i = 0; i < Usr->getNumOperands(); ++i) { 0
1380 Value *Op = Usr->getOperand(i); 0
1381 ValueLatticeElement OpLatticeVal = ----
1382 getValueFromCondition(Op, Condition, isTrueDest); 0
1383 if (std::optional OpConst = 0
1384 OpLatticeVal.asConstantInteger()) { 0
1385 Result = constantFoldUser(Usr, Op, *OpConst, DL); 0
1386 break; 0
1387 } 0
1388 } 0
1389 } ----
1390 } ----
1391 } ----
1392 if (!Result.isOverdefined()) 0
1393 return Result; 0
1394 } 0
1395 } ----
1396 ----
1397 // If the edge was formed by a switch on the value, then we may know exactly ----
1398 // what it is. ----
1399 if (SwitchInst *SI = dyn_cast(BBFrom->getTerminator())) { 0
1400 Value *Condition = SI->getCondition(); 0
1401 if (!isa(Val->getType())) 0
1402 return std::nullopt; 0
1403 bool ValUsesConditionAndMayBeFoldable = false; 0
1404 if (Condition != Val) { 0
1405 // Check if Val has Condition as an operand. ----
1406 if (User *Usr = dyn_cast(Val)) 0
1407 ValUsesConditionAndMayBeFoldable = isOperationFoldable(Usr) && 0
1408 usesOperand(Usr, Condition); 0
1409 if (!ValUsesConditionAndMayBeFoldable) 0
1410 return std::nullopt; 0
1411 } ----
1412 assert((Condition == Val || ValUsesConditionAndMayBeFoldable) && 0
1413 "Condition != Val nor Val doesn't use Condition"); ----
1414 ----
1415 bool DefaultCase = SI->getDefaultDest() == BBTo; 0
1416 unsigned BitWidth = Val->getType()->getIntegerBitWidth(); 0
1417 ConstantRange EdgesVals(BitWidth, DefaultCase/*isFullSet*/); 0
1418 ----
1419 for (auto Case : SI->cases()) { 0
1420 APInt CaseValue = Case.getCaseValue()->getValue(); 0
1421 ConstantRange EdgeVal(CaseValue); 0
1422 if (ValUsesConditionAndMayBeFoldable) { 0
1423 User *Usr = cast(Val); 0
1424 const DataLayout &DL = BBTo->getModule()->getDataLayout(); 0
1425 ValueLatticeElement EdgeLatticeVal = ----
1426 constantFoldUser(Usr, Condition, CaseValue, DL); 0
1427 if (EdgeLatticeVal.isOverdefined()) 0
1428 return std::nullopt; 0
1429 EdgeVal = EdgeLatticeVal.getConstantRange(); 0
1430 } 0
1431 if (DefaultCase) { 0
1432 // It is possible that the default destination is the destination of ----
1433 // some cases. We cannot perform difference for those cases. ----
1434 // We know Condition != CaseValue in BBTo. In some cases we can use ----
1435 // this to infer Val == f(Condition) is != f(CaseValue). For now, we ----
1436 // only do this when f is identity (i.e. Val == Condition), but we ----
1437 // should be able to do this for any injective f. ----
1438 if (Case.getCaseSuccessor() != BBTo && Condition == Val) 0
1439 EdgesVals = EdgesVals.difference(EdgeVal); 0
1440 } else if (Case.getCaseSuccessor() == BBTo) 0
1441 EdgesVals = EdgesVals.unionWith(EdgeVal); 0
1442 } 0
1443 return ValueLatticeElement::getRange(std::move(EdgesVals)); 0
1444 } 0
1445 return std::nullopt; 0
1446 } ----
1447 ----
1448 /// Compute the value of Val on the edge BBFrom -> BBTo or the value at ----
1449 /// the basic block if the edge does not constrain Val. ----
1450 std::optional ----
1451 LazyValueInfoImpl::getEdgeValue(Value *Val, BasicBlock *BBFrom, 0
1452 BasicBlock *BBTo, Instruction *CxtI) { ----
1453 // If already a constant, there is nothing to compute. ----
1454 if (Constant *VC = dyn_cast(Val)) 0
1455 return ValueLatticeElement::get(VC); 0
1456 ----
1457 ValueLatticeElement LocalResult = ----
1458 getEdgeValueLocal(Val, BBFrom, BBTo) 0
1459 .value_or(ValueLatticeElement::getOverdefined()); 0
1460 if (hasSingleValue(LocalResult)) 0
1461 // Can't get any more precise here ----
1462 return LocalResult; 0
1463 ----
1464 std::optional OptInBlock = ----
1465 getBlockValue(Val, BBFrom, BBFrom->getTerminator()); 0
1466 if (!OptInBlock) 0
1467 return std::nullopt; 0
1468 ValueLatticeElement &InBlock = *OptInBlock; 0
1469 ----
1470 // We can use the context instruction (generically the ultimate instruction ----
1471 // the calling pass is trying to simplify) here, even though the result of ----
1472 // this function is generally cached when called from the solve* functions ----
1473 // (and that cached result might be used with queries using a different ----
1474 // context instruction), because when this function is called from the solve* ----
1475 // functions, the context instruction is not provided. When called from ----
1476 // LazyValueInfoImpl::getValueOnEdge, the context instruction is provided, ----
1477 // but then the result is not cached. ----
1478 intersectAssumeOrGuardBlockValueConstantRange(Val, InBlock, CxtI); 0
1479 ----
1480 return intersect(LocalResult, InBlock); 0
1481 } 0
1482 ----
1483 ValueLatticeElement LazyValueInfoImpl::getValueInBlock(Value *V, BasicBlock *BB, 0
1484 Instruction *CxtI) { ----
1485 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "LVI Getting block end value " << *V << " at '" 0
1486 << BB->getName() << "'\n"); ----
1487 ----
1488 assert(BlockValueStack.empty() && BlockValueSet.empty()); 0
1489 std::optional OptResult = getBlockValue(V, BB, CxtI); 0
1490 if (!OptResult) { 0
1491 solve(); 0
1492 OptResult = getBlockValue(V, BB, CxtI); 0
1493 assert(OptResult && "Value not available after solving"); 0
1494 } ----
1495 ----
1496 ValueLatticeElement Result = *OptResult; 0
1497 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " Result = " << Result << "\n"); 0
1498 return Result; 0
1499 } 0
1500 ----
1501 ValueLatticeElement LazyValueInfoImpl::getValueAt(Value *V, Instruction *CxtI) { 0
1502 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "LVI Getting value " << *V << " at '" << CxtI->getName() 0
1503 << "'\n"); ----
1504 ----
1505 if (auto *C = dyn_cast(V)) 0
1506 return ValueLatticeElement::get(C); 0
1507 ----
1508 ValueLatticeElement Result = ValueLatticeElement::getOverdefined(); 0
1509 if (auto *I = dyn_cast(V)) 0
1510 Result = getFromRangeMetadata(I); 0
1511 intersectAssumeOrGuardBlockValueConstantRange(V, Result, CxtI); 0
1512 ----
1513 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " Result = " << Result << "\n"); 0
1514 return Result; 0
1515 } 0
1516 ----
1517 ValueLatticeElement LazyValueInfoImpl:: 0
1518 getValueOnEdge(Value *V, BasicBlock *FromBB, BasicBlock *ToBB, ----
1519 Instruction *CxtI) { ----
1520 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "LVI Getting edge value " << *V << " from '" 0
1521 << FromBB->getName() << "' to '" << ToBB->getName() ----
1522 << "'\n"); ----
1523 ----
1524 std::optional Result = ----
1525 getEdgeValue(V, FromBB, ToBB, CxtI); 0
1526 if (!Result) { 0
1527 solve(); 0
1528 Result = getEdgeValue(V, FromBB, ToBB, CxtI); 0
1529 assert(Result && "More work to do after problem solved?"); 0
1530 } ----
1531 ----
1532 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " Result = " << *Result << "\n"); 0
1533 return *Result; 0
1534 } 0

1537 BasicBlock *NewSucc) { ----
1538 TheCache.threadEdgeImpl(OldSucc, NewSucc); 0
1539 } 0

1545 /// This lazily constructs the LazyValueInfoImpl. ----
1546 static LazyValueInfoImpl &getImpl(void *&PImpl, AssumptionCache *AC, 0
1547 const Module *M) { ----
1548 if (!PImpl) { 0
1549 assert(M && "getCache() called with a null Module"); 0
1550 const DataLayout &DL = M->getDataLayout(); 0
1551 Function *GuardDecl = M->getFunction( 0
1552 Intrinsic::getName(Intrinsic::experimental_guard)); ----
1553 PImpl = new LazyValueInfoImpl(AC, DL, GuardDecl); 0
1554 } ----
1555 return *static_cast(PImpl); 0
1556 } ----

1562 if (Info.PImpl) 0

1564 ----
1565 // Fully lazy. ----
1566 return false; 0
1567 } ----

1590 // result directly or if any of its dependencies have been invalidated. ----
1591 auto PAC = PA.getChecker(); 0

1593 return true; 0

1595 return false; 0
1596 } ----

1600 LazyValueInfo LazyValueAnalysis::run(Function &F, 0
1601 FunctionAnalysisManager &FAM) { ----
1602 auto &AC = FAM.getResult(F); 0
1603 auto &TLI = FAM.getResult(F); 0
1604 ----
1605 return LazyValueInfo(&AC, &F.getParent()->getDataLayout(), &TLI); 0
1606 } ----
1607 ----
1608 /// Returns true if we can statically tell that this value will never be a ----
1609 /// "useful" constant. In practice, this means we've got something like an ----
1610 /// alloca or a malloc call for which a comparison against a constant can ----
1611 /// only be guarding dead code. Note that we are potentially giving up some ----
1612 /// precision in dead code (a constant result) in favour of avoiding a ----
1613 /// expensive search for a easily answered common query. ----
1614 static bool isKnownNonConstant(Value *V) { 0
1615 V = V->stripPointerCasts(); 0
1616 // The return val of alloc cannot be a Constant. ----
1617 if (isa(V)) 0
1618 return true; 0
1619 return false; 0
1620 } ----
1621 ----
1622 Constant *LazyValueInfo::getConstant(Value *V, Instruction *CxtI) { 0
1623 // Bail out early if V is known not to be a Constant. ----
1624 if (isKnownNonConstant(V)) 0
1625 return nullptr; 0
1626 ----
1627 BasicBlock *BB = CxtI->getParent(); 0
1628 ValueLatticeElement Result = ----
1629 getImpl(PImpl, AC, BB->getModule()).getValueInBlock(V, BB, CxtI); 0
1630 ----
1631 if (Result.isConstant()) 0
1632 return Result.getConstant(); 0
1633 if (Result.isConstantRange()) { 0
1634 const ConstantRange &CR = Result.getConstantRange(); 0
1635 if (const APInt *SingleVal = CR.getSingleElement()) 0
1636 return ConstantInt::get(V->getContext(), *SingleVal); 0
1637 } ----
1638 return nullptr; 0
1639 } 0
1640 ----
1641 ConstantRange LazyValueInfo::getConstantRange(Value *V, Instruction *CxtI, 0
1642 bool UndefAllowed) { ----
1643 assert(V->getType()->isIntegerTy()); 0
1644 unsigned Width = V->getType()->getIntegerBitWidth(); 0
1645 BasicBlock *BB = CxtI->getParent(); 0
1646 ValueLatticeElement Result = ----
1647 getImpl(PImpl, AC, BB->getModule()).getValueInBlock(V, BB, CxtI); 0
1648 if (Result.isUnknown()) 0
1649 return ConstantRange::getEmpty(Width); 0
1650 if (Result.isConstantRange(UndefAllowed)) 0
1651 return Result.getConstantRange(UndefAllowed); 0
1652 // We represent ConstantInt constants as constant ranges but other kinds ----
1653 // of integer constants, i.e. ConstantExpr will be tagged as constants ----
1654 assert(!(Result.isConstant() && isa(Result.getConstant())) && 0
1655 "ConstantInt value must be represented as constantrange"); ----
1656 return ConstantRange::getFull(Width); 0
1657 } 0
1658 ----
1659 ConstantRange LazyValueInfo::getConstantRangeAtUse(const Use &U, 0
1660 bool UndefAllowed) { ----
1661 Value *V = U.get(); 0
1662 ConstantRange CR = ----
1663 getConstantRange(V, cast(U.getUser()), UndefAllowed); 0
1664 ----
1665 // Check whether the only (possibly transitive) use of the value is in a ----
1666 // position where V can be constrained by a select or branch condition. ----
1667 const Use *CurrU = &U; 0
1668 // TODO: Increase limit? ----
1669 const unsigned MaxUsesToInspect = 3; 0
1670 for (unsigned I = 0; I < MaxUsesToInspect; ++I) { 0
1671 std::optional CondVal; 0
1672 auto *CurrI = cast(CurrU->getUser()); 0
1673 if (auto *SI = dyn_cast(CurrI)) { 0
1674 // If the value is undef, a different value may be chosen in ----
1675 // the select condition and at use. ----
1676 if (!isGuaranteedNotToBeUndefOrPoison(SI->getCondition(), AC)) 0
1677 break; 0
1678 if (CurrU->getOperandNo() == 1) 0
1679 CondVal = getValueFromCondition(V, SI->getCondition(), true); 0
1680 else if (CurrU->getOperandNo() == 2) 0
1681 CondVal = getValueFromCondition(V, SI->getCondition(), false); 0
1682 } else if (auto *PHI = dyn_cast(CurrI)) { 0
1683 // TODO: Use non-local query? ----
1684 CondVal = ----
1685 getEdgeValueLocal(V, PHI->getIncomingBlock(*CurrU), PHI->getParent()); 0
1686 } ----
1687 if (CondVal && CondVal->isConstantRange()) 0
1688 CR = CR.intersectWith(CondVal->getConstantRange()); 0
1689 ----
1690 // Only follow one-use chain, to allow direct intersection of conditions. ----
1691 // If there are multiple uses, we would have to intersect with the union of ----
1692 // all conditions at different uses. ----
1693 // Stop walking if we hit a non-speculatable instruction. Even if the ----
1694 // result is only used under a specific condition, executing the ----
1695 // instruction itself may cause side effects or UB already. ----
1696 // This also disallows looking through phi nodes: If the phi node is part ----
1697 // of a cycle, we might end up reasoning about values from different cycle ----
1698 // iterations (PR60629). ----
1699 if (!CurrI->hasOneUse() || !isSafeToSpeculativelyExecute(CurrI)) 0
1700 break; 0
1701 CurrU = &*CurrI->use_begin(); 0
1702 } 0
1703 return CR; 0
1704 } ----
1705 ----
1706 /// Determine whether the specified value is known to be a ----
1707 /// constant on the specified edge. Return null if not. ----
1708 Constant *LazyValueInfo::getConstantOnEdge(Value *V, BasicBlock *FromBB, 0
1709 BasicBlock *ToBB, ----
1710 Instruction *CxtI) { ----
1711 Module *M = FromBB->getModule(); 0
1712 ValueLatticeElement Result = ----
1713 getImpl(PImpl, AC, M).getValueOnEdge(V, FromBB, ToBB, CxtI); 0
1714 ----
1715 if (Result.isConstant()) 0
1716 return Result.getConstant(); 0
1717 if (Result.isConstantRange()) { 0
1718 const ConstantRange &CR = Result.getConstantRange(); 0
1719 if (const APInt *SingleVal = CR.getSingleElement()) 0
1720 return ConstantInt::get(V->getContext(), *SingleVal); 0
1721 } ----
1722 return nullptr; 0
1723 } 0
1724 ----
1725 ConstantRange LazyValueInfo::getConstantRangeOnEdge(Value *V, 0
1726 BasicBlock *FromBB, ----
1727 BasicBlock *ToBB, ----
1728 Instruction *CxtI) { ----
1729 unsigned Width = V->getType()->getIntegerBitWidth(); 0
1730 Module *M = FromBB->getModule(); 0
1731 ValueLatticeElement Result = ----
1732 getImpl(PImpl, AC, M).getValueOnEdge(V, FromBB, ToBB, CxtI); 0
1733 ----
1734 if (Result.isUnknown()) 0
1735 return ConstantRange::getEmpty(Width); 0
1736 if (Result.isConstantRange()) 0
1737 return Result.getConstantRange(); 0
1738 // We represent ConstantInt constants as constant ranges but other kinds ----
1739 // of integer constants, i.e. ConstantExpr will be tagged as constants ----
1740 assert(!(Result.isConstant() && isa(Result.getConstant())) && 0
1741 "ConstantInt value must be represented as constantrange"); ----
1742 return ConstantRange::getFull(Width); 0
1743 } 0
1744 ----
1745 static LazyValueInfo::Tristate ----
1746 getPredicateResult(unsigned Pred, Constant *C, const ValueLatticeElement &Val, 0
1747 const DataLayout &DL, TargetLibraryInfo *TLI) { ----
1748 // If we know the value is a constant, evaluate the conditional. ----
1749 Constant *Res = nullptr; 0
1750 if (Val.isConstant()) { 0
1751 Res = ConstantFoldCompareInstOperands(Pred, Val.getConstant(), C, DL, TLI); 0
1752 if (ConstantInt *ResCI = dyn_cast_or_null(Res)) 0
1753 return ResCI->isZero() ? LazyValueInfo::False : LazyValueInfo::True; 0
1754 return LazyValueInfo::Unknown; 0
1755 } ----
1756 ----
1757 if (Val.isConstantRange()) { 0
1758 ConstantInt *CI = dyn_cast(C); 0
1759 if (!CI) return LazyValueInfo::Unknown; 0
1760 ----
1761 const ConstantRange &CR = Val.getConstantRange(); 0
1762 if (Pred == ICmpInst::ICMP_EQ) { 0
1763 if (!CR.contains(CI->getValue())) 0
1764 return LazyValueInfo::False; 0
1765 ----
1766 if (CR.isSingleElement()) 0
1767 return LazyValueInfo::True; 0
1768 } else if (Pred == ICmpInst::ICMP_NE) { 0
1769 if (!CR.contains(CI->getValue())) 0
1770 return LazyValueInfo::True; 0
1771 ----
1772 if (CR.isSingleElement()) 0
1773 return LazyValueInfo::False; 0
1774 } else { ----
1775 // Handle more complex predicates. ----
1776 ConstantRange TrueValues = ConstantRange::makeExactICmpRegion( ----
1777 (ICmpInst::Predicate)Pred, CI->getValue()); 0
1778 if (TrueValues.contains(CR)) 0
1779 return LazyValueInfo::True; 0
1780 if (TrueValues.inverse().contains(CR)) 0
1781 return LazyValueInfo::False; 0
1782 } 0
1783 return LazyValueInfo::Unknown; 0
1784 } ----
1785 ----
1786 if (Val.isNotConstant()) { 0
1787 // If this is an equality comparison, we can try to fold it knowing that ----
1788 // "V != C1". ----
1789 if (Pred == ICmpInst::ICMP_EQ) { 0
1790 // !C1 == C -> false iff C1 == C. ----
1791 Res = ConstantFoldCompareInstOperands(ICmpInst::ICMP_NE, 0
1792 Val.getNotConstant(), C, DL, ----
1793 TLI); ----
1794 if (Res && Res->isNullValue()) 0
1795 return LazyValueInfo::False; 0
1796 } else if (Pred == ICmpInst::ICMP_NE) { 0
1797 // !C1 != C -> true iff C1 == C. ----
1798 Res = ConstantFoldCompareInstOperands(ICmpInst::ICMP_NE, 0
1799 Val.getNotConstant(), C, DL, ----
1800 TLI); ----
1801 if (Res && Res->isNullValue()) 0
1802 return LazyValueInfo::True; 0
1803 } ----
1804 return LazyValueInfo::Unknown; 0
1805 } ----
1806 ----
1807 return LazyValueInfo::Unknown; 0
1808 } ----

1810 /// Determine whether the specified value comparison with a constant is known to ----
1811 /// be true or false on the specified CFG edge. Pred is a CmpInst predicate. ----
1812 LazyValueInfo::Tristate ----
1813 LazyValueInfo::getPredicateOnEdge(unsigned Pred, Value *V, Constant *C, 0
1814 BasicBlock *FromBB, BasicBlock *ToBB, ----
1815 Instruction *CxtI) { ----
1816 Module *M = FromBB->getModule(); 0
1817 ValueLatticeElement Result = ----
1818 getImpl(PImpl, AC, M).getValueOnEdge(V, FromBB, ToBB, CxtI); 0
1819 ----
1820 return getPredicateResult(Pred, C, Result, M->getDataLayout(), TLI); 0

1822 ----
1823 LazyValueInfo::Tristate ----
1824 LazyValueInfo::getPredicateAt(unsigned Pred, Value *V, Constant *C, 0
1825 Instruction *CxtI, bool UseBlockValue) { ----
1826 // Is or is not NonNull are common predicates being queried. If ----
1827 // isKnownNonZero can tell us the result of the predicate, we can ----
1828 // return it quickly. But this is only a fastpath, and falling ----
1829 // through would still be correct. ----
1830 Module *M = CxtI->getModule(); 0
1831 const DataLayout &DL = M->getDataLayout(); 0
1832 if (V->getType()->isPointerTy() && C->isNullValue() && 0
1833 isKnownNonZero(V->stripPointerCastsSameRepresentation(), DL)) { 0
1834 if (Pred == ICmpInst::ICMP_EQ) 0
1835 return LazyValueInfo::False; 0
1836 else if (Pred == ICmpInst::ICMP_NE) 0
1837 return LazyValueInfo::True; 0
1838 } ----
1839 ----
1840 ValueLatticeElement Result = UseBlockValue ----
1841 ? getImpl(PImpl, AC, M).getValueInBlock(V, CxtI->getParent(), CxtI) 0
1842 : getImpl(PImpl, AC, M).getValueAt(V, CxtI); 0
1843 Tristate Ret = getPredicateResult(Pred, C, Result, DL, TLI); 0
1844 if (Ret != Unknown) 0
1845 return Ret; 0
1846 ----
1847 // Note: The following bit of code is somewhat distinct from the rest of LVI; ----
1848 // LVI as a whole tries to compute a lattice value which is conservatively ----
1849 // correct at a given location. In this case, we have a predicate which we ----
1850 // weren't able to prove about the merged result, and we're pushing that ----
1851 // predicate back along each incoming edge to see if we can prove it ----
1852 // separately for each input. As a motivating example, consider: ----
1853 // bb1: ----
1854 // %v1 = ... ; constantrange<1, 5> ----
1855 // br label %merge ----
1856 // bb2: ----
1857 // %v2 = ... ; constantrange<10, 20> ----
1858 // br label %merge ----
1859 // merge: ----
1860 // %phi = phi [%v1, %v2] ; constantrange<1,20> ----
1861 // %pred = icmp eq i32 %phi, 8 ----
1862 // We can't tell from the lattice value for '%phi' that '%pred' is false ----
1863 // along each path, but by checking the predicate over each input separately, ----
1864 // we can. ----
1865 // We limit the search to one step backwards from the current BB and value. ----
1866 // We could consider extending this to search further backwards through the ----
1867 // CFG and/or value graph, but there are non-obvious compile time vs quality ----
1868 // tradeoffs. ----
1869 BasicBlock *BB = CxtI->getParent(); 0
1870 ----
1871 // Function entry or an unreachable block. Bail to avoid confusing ----
1872 // analysis below. ----
1873 pred_iterator PI = pred_begin(BB), PE = pred_end(BB); 0
1874 if (PI == PE) 0
1875 return Unknown; 0
1876 ----
1877 // If V is a PHI node in the same block as the context, we need to ask ----
1878 // questions about the predicate as applied to the incoming value along ----
1879 // each edge. This is useful for eliminating cases where the predicate is ----
1880 // known along all incoming edges. ----
1881 if (auto *PHI = dyn_cast(V)) 0
1882 if (PHI->getParent() == BB) { 0
1883 Tristate Baseline = Unknown; 0
1884 for (unsigned i = 0, e = PHI->getNumIncomingValues(); i < e; i++) { 0
1885 Value *Incoming = PHI->getIncomingValue(i); 0
1886 BasicBlock *PredBB = PHI->getIncomingBlock(i); 0
1887 // Note that PredBB may be BB itself. ----
1888 Tristate Result = ----
1889 getPredicateOnEdge(Pred, Incoming, C, PredBB, BB, CxtI); 0
1890 ----
1891 // Keep going as long as we've seen a consistent known result for ----
1892 // all inputs. ----
1893 Baseline = (i == 0) ? Result /* First iteration */ 0
1894 : (Baseline == Result ? Baseline 0
1895 : Unknown); /* All others */ ----
1896 if (Baseline == Unknown) 0
1897 break; 0
1898 } ----
1899 if (Baseline != Unknown) 0
1900 return Baseline; 0
1901 } ----
1902 ----
1903 // For a comparison where the V is outside this block, it's possible ----
1904 // that we've branched on it before. Look to see if the value is known ----
1905 // on all incoming edges. ----
1906 if (!isa(V) || cast(V)->getParent() != BB) { 0
1907 // For predecessor edge, determine if the comparison is true or false ----
1908 // on that edge. If they're all true or all false, we can conclude ----
1909 // the value of the comparison in this block. ----
1910 Tristate Baseline = getPredicateOnEdge(Pred, V, C, *PI, BB, CxtI); 0
1911 if (Baseline != Unknown) { 0
1912 // Check that all remaining incoming values match the first one. ----
1913 while (++PI != PE) { 0
1914 Tristate Ret = getPredicateOnEdge(Pred, V, C, *PI, BB, CxtI); 0
1915 if (Ret != Baseline) 0
1916 break; 0
1917 } ----
1918 // If we terminated early, then one of the values didn't match. ----
1919 if (PI == PE) { 0
1920 return Baseline; 0
1921 } ----
1922 } ----
1923 } ----
1924 ----
1925 return Unknown; 0
1926 } 0
1927 ----
1928 LazyValueInfo::Tristate LazyValueInfo::getPredicateAt(unsigned P, Value *LHS, 0
1929 Value *RHS, ----
1930 Instruction *CxtI, ----
1931 bool UseBlockValue) { ----
1932 CmpInst::Predicate Pred = (CmpInst::Predicate)P; 0
1933 ----
1934 if (auto *C = dyn_cast(RHS)) 0
1935 return getPredicateAt(P, LHS, C, CxtI, UseBlockValue); 0
1936 if (auto *C = dyn_cast(LHS)) 0
1937 return getPredicateAt(CmpInst::getSwappedPredicate(Pred), RHS, C, CxtI, 0
1938 UseBlockValue); 0
1939 ----
1940 // Got two non-Constant values. Try to determine the comparison results based ----
1941 // on the block values of the two operands, e.g. because they have ----
1942 // non-overlapping ranges. ----
1943 if (UseBlockValue) { 0
1944 Module *M = CxtI->getModule(); 0
1945 ValueLatticeElement L = ----
1946 getImpl(PImpl, AC, M).getValueInBlock(LHS, CxtI->getParent(), CxtI); 0
1947 if (L.isOverdefined()) 0
1948 return LazyValueInfo::Unknown; 0
1949 ----
1950 ValueLatticeElement R = ----
1951 getImpl(PImpl, AC, M).getValueInBlock(RHS, CxtI->getParent(), CxtI); 0
1952 Type *Ty = CmpInst::makeCmpResultType(LHS->getType()); 0
1953 if (Constant *Res = L.getCompare((CmpInst::Predicate)P, Ty, R, 0
1954 M->getDataLayout())) { ----
1955 if (Res->isNullValue()) 0
1956 return LazyValueInfo::False; 0
1957 if (Res->isOneValue()) 0
1958 return LazyValueInfo::True; 0
1959 } ----
1960 } 0
1961 return LazyValueInfo::Unknown; 0
1962 } ----

97 // Undefined is the strongest state. It means the value is known to be along 97 // Undefined is the strongest state. It means the value is known to be along
98 // an unreachable path. 98 // an unreachable path.
99 if (A.isUnknown()) 99 if (A.isUnknown())
100 return A; 100 return A;
101 if (B.isUnknown()) 101 if (B.isUnknown())
102 return B; 102 return B;
103 103
104 // If we gave up for one, but got a useable fact from the other, use it. 104 // If we gave up for one, but got a useable fact from the other, use it.
105 if (A.isOverdefined()) 105 if (A.isOverdefined())

285 void LazyValueInfoCache::threadEdgeImpl(BasicBlock *OldSucc, 285 void LazyValueInfoCache::threadEdgeImpl(BasicBlock *OldSucc,
286 BasicBlock *NewSucc) { 286 BasicBlock *NewSucc) {
287 // When an edge in the graph has been threaded, values that we could not 287 // When an edge in the graph has been threaded, values that we could not
288 // determine a value for before (i.e. were marked overdefined) may be 288 // determine a value for before (i.e. were marked overdefined) may be
289 // possible to solve now. We do NOT try to proactively update these values. 289 // possible to solve now. We do NOT try to proactively update these values.
290 // Instead, we clear their entries from the cache, and allow lazy updating to 290 // Instead, we clear their entries from the cache, and allow lazy updating to
291 // recompute them when needed. 291 // recompute them when needed.
292 292
293 // The updating process is fairly simple: we need to drop cached info 293 // The updating process is fairly simple: we need to drop cached info
294 // for all values that were marked overdefined in OldSucc, and for those same 294 // for all values that were marked overdefined in OldSucc, and for those same
295 // values in any successor of OldSucc (except NewSucc) in which they were 295 // values in any successor of OldSucc (except NewSucc) in which they were
296 // also marked overdefined. 296 // also marked overdefined.
297 std::vector worklist; 297 std::vector worklist;
298 worklist.push_back(OldSucc); 298 worklist.push_back(OldSucc);
299 299
300 const BlockCacheEntry *Entry = getBlockEntry(OldSucc); 300 const BlockCacheEntry *Entry = getBlockEntry(OldSucc);
301 if (!Entry || Entry->OverDefined.empty()) 301 if (!Entry || Entry->OverDefined.empty())
302 return; // Nothing to process here. 302 return; // Nothing to process here.
303 SmallVector ValsToClear(Entry->OverDefined.begin(), 303 SmallVector ValsToClear(Entry->OverDefined.begin(),
304 Entry->OverDefined.end()); 304 Entry->OverDefined.end());
305 305
306 // Use a worklist to perform a depth-first search of OldSucc's successors. 306 // Use a worklist to perform a depth-first search of OldSucc's successors.
307 // NOTE: We do not need a visited list since any blocks we have already 307 // NOTE: We do not need a visited list since any blocks we have already
308 // visited will have had their overdefined markers cleared already, and we 308 // visited will have had their overdefined markers cleared already, and we
309 // thus won't loop to their successors. 309 // thus won't loop to their successors.
310 while (!worklist.empty()) { 310 while (!worklist.empty()) {
311 BasicBlock *ToUpdate = worklist.back(); 311 BasicBlock *ToUpdate = worklist.back();
312 worklist.pop_back(); 312 worklist.pop_back();
313 313
314 // Skip blocks only accessible through NewSucc. 314 // Skip blocks only accessible through NewSucc.
315 if (ToUpdate == NewSucc) continue; 315 if (ToUpdate == NewSucc) continue;
316 316
317 // If a value was marked overdefined in OldSucc, and is here too... 317 // If a value was marked overdefined in OldSucc, and is here too...
318 auto OI = BlockCache.find_as(ToUpdate); 318 auto OI = BlockCache.find_as(ToUpdate);
319 if (OI == BlockCache.end() || OI->second->OverDefined.empty()) 319 if (OI == BlockCache.end() || OI->second->OverDefined.empty())
320 continue; 320 continue;
321 auto &ValueSet = OI->second->OverDefined; 321 auto &ValueSet = OI->second->OverDefined;
322 322
323 bool changed = false; 323 bool changed = false;
324 for (Value *V : ValsToClear) { 324 for (Value *V : ValsToClear) {
325 if (!ValueSet.erase(V)) 325 if (!ValueSet.erase(V))
326 continue; 326 continue;
327 327
328 // If we removed anything, then we potentially need to update 328 // If we removed anything, then we potentially need to update
329 // blocks successors too. 329 // blocks successors too.
330 changed = true; 330 changed = true;
331 } 331 }
332 332
333 if (!changed) continue; 333 if (!changed) continue;
